  "prompt": "Knighthood: Is it possible for a non-native British citizen to be knighted?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible for a non-native British citizen to be knighted, though the process is slightly different:\n\n1. Honorary Knighthood:\n- Non-British citizens can receive an honorary knighthood\n- They can use the title \"Honorary Knight\" but cannot use \"Sir\" before their name\n- Common recipients include international leaders, philanthropists, and cultural figures\n\n2. Commonwealth Citizens:\n- Citizens from Commonwealth countries can receive a full knighthood\n- They can use the title \"Sir\" and have full knightly honors\n- Examples include people from Canada, Australia, New Zealand, etc.\n\n3. Citizenship Requirement:\n- Permanent residents or naturalized British citizens can receive a full knighthood\n- They must typically have made significant contributions to the UK\n\n4. Types of Knighthoods:\n- Knight Bachelor\n- Order of the British Empire (KBE)\n- Other specific orders of chivalry\n\n5. Selection Process:\n- Nominated through various channels\n- Reviewed by honors committees\n- Approved by the monarch\n- Typically recognized for outstanding achievements in public service, arts, science, or business\n\nNotable non-British knights include Elton John (British), Laurence Olivier (British), Bill Gates (US), and Bono (Irish).\n\nThe process is selective and based on merit and contribution to society.",
